# SUNO Album Studio OS

Markdown-first creative OS for **any musician** — SUNO albums, archive, learnings. Not a code app.

> Albums may change clothes; the body must remain recognizable.

## Read first

| Task | Start here |
|------|------------|
| Any session | `00_system/project_instructions.md`, `README.md` |
| First run | `ONBOARDING.md` → `/onboard artist` |
| Slash command | `00_system/commands.md` + `00_system/mandatory_reads.md` for that command |
| Orchestrate album | `00_system/album_orchestrator.md` + `mandatory_reads.md` (orchestrator) |
| Creative identity | `01_artist/artist_dna.md` |
| User feedback words | `01_artist/feedback_dictionary.md` |

## Repo map

```text
00_system/     workflow, commands, SUNO guide
01_artist/     DNA, style reference, cover guide
02_albums/     one folder per album (_album_template for new)
03_global_learnings/
04_templates/
05_catalog/
06_integrations/  optional studio-suno CLI
```

Album slugs: lowercase hyphens (`my-album`, `track-slug`). No `references/` folder — docs live in place.

## Non-negotiables

1. Identity over genre — artist body stays recognizable across albums.
2. Life beats concept — reject dead music even if the idea is right.
3. One song at a time — depth over batch work.
4. Prefer **updating existing Markdown** over new files.
5. Know workflow phase (`00_system/workflow.md`) — don't jump to SUNO before a song brief unless the user asks.
6. Warm, human tone — creative partner, not compliance docs.
7. No git commits unless the user asks.

## Protect / avoid

Read from `01_artist/artist_identity.md` after onboarding. Typical defaults: warmth, sincerity, organic instruments, lived insight.

Avoid: genre cosplay, moralizing, self-help tone, synthetic gloss, over-engineering the repo.
